<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,150,465]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,304,187,213]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Remark.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Walckenaer" box="[312,526,187,213]" firstAuthor="Walckenaer" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" refId="ref78887" refString="Walckenaer, C. A. (1837) Histoire naturelle des insectes. Apteres. Tome premier. Roret, Paris, 682 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 61095" type="book" year="1837">Walckenaer (1837)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Bonnet" authorityYear="1959" box="[649,833,187,212]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Tapinauchenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanctivincenti">
<emphasis box="[649,833,187,212]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">T. sanctivincenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[903,1131,187,213]" name="Saint Vincent Island" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Saint Vincent Island</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1148,1277,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–23. 21" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1339,1363]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1315]" captionTargetId="figure-19@32.[151,1435,181,1315]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 21–23. 21, Map showing geographic records (dots) of Tapinauchenius species. 22, detail of the geographic records (dots) of T. sanctivincenti, T. latipes, T. polybotes and T. rasti. 23, detail of the geographic records (dots) of T. plumipes (red) and T. gretae n. sp. (black) in Central Amazonia, Brazil. Tapinauchenius plumipes (red), T. sanctivincenti (pink), T. latipes (green), T. brunneus (brown), T. cupreus (yellow), T. polybotes (purple), T. rasti (light blue), T. gretae n. sp. (black). MI = Mustique island; SL = Saint Lucia island; SV = Saint Vincent island; UI = Union island; TR = Trinidad; VE = Venezuela." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6253255" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6253255/files/figure.png" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Figs 21–22</figureCitation>
) in the Caribbean, with no further information. As the 
<typeStatus box="[628,676,223,249]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
seems to be lost, 
<bibRefCitation author="Husser" box="[884,1045,223,249]" firstAuthor="Husser" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="59 - 93" refId="ref76547" refString="Husser, M. (2018) A first phylogenetic analysis reveals a new arboreal tarantula genus from South America with description of a new species and two new species of Tapinauchenius Ausserer, 1871 (Araneae, Mygalomorphae, Theraphosidae). ZooKeys, 784, 59 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 784.26521" type="journal article" year="2018">Hüsser (2018)</bibRefCitation>
suggested it should be considered as 
<emphasis box="[183,394,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">species inquirenda</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[461,509,259,285]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
locality is an island, thus there is the possibility of recollecting specimens and to redescribe it; therefore, we consider it a valid species. More recently, 
<bibRefCitation author="Husser" box="[935,1095,295,321]" firstAuthor="Husser" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="59 - 93" refId="ref76547" refString="Husser, M. (2018) A first phylogenetic analysis reveals a new arboreal tarantula genus from South America with description of a new species and two new species of Tapinauchenius Ausserer, 1871 (Araneae, Mygalomorphae, Theraphosidae). ZooKeys, 784, 59 - 93. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 784.26521" type="journal article" year="2018">Hüsser (2018)</bibRefCitation>
described two new species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Husser" authorityYear="2018" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Tapinauchenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polybotes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">T. polybotes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from 
<collectingCountry box="[336,541,331,358]" name="Saint Lucia Island" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Saint Lucia Island</collectingCountry>
) and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Husser" authorityYear="2018" box="[603,681,331,356]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Tapinauchenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rasti">
<emphasis box="[603,681,331,356]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">T. rasti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from Union Island) both in the same Archipelago of 
<collectingCountry name="Saint Vincent Island" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Saint Vincent Island</collectingCountry>
. As all these islands are relatively close, there is the possibility of one of these two species be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Bonnet" authorityYear="1959" box="[209,392,403,428]" class="Arachnida" family="Theraphosidae" genus="Tapinauchenius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanctivincenti">
<emphasis box="[209,392,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">T. sanctivincenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, this question will only be resolved after specimens from 
<collectingCountry box="[1166,1394,403,429]" name="Saint Vincent Island" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Saint Vincent Island</collectingCountry>
are available for redescription and comparison.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
